The '''Gbaya languages''', also known as '''Gbaya–Manza–Ngbaka''', are a family of perhaps a dozen languages spoken mainly in the western [[Central African Republic]] and across the border in [[Cameroon]], with one language (Ngbaka) in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], with a few small languages in the [[Republic of the Congo]]. Many of the languages go by the ethnic name ''[[Gbaya people|Gbaya]],'' though the largest, with over a million speakers, is called [[Ngbaka language|Ngbaka]], a name shared with the [[Ngbaka languages]] of the [[Ubangian languages|Ubangian]] family.

==Classification==
The Gbaya languages were once thought to be part of the [[Ubangian languages|Ubangian]] family. However, Moñino (2010), followed by Blench (2012), propose that they may instead be most closely related to the [[Central Gur languages]], or perhaps constitute an independent branch of Niger–Congo, but that they do not form a group with Ubangian.<ref>Roger Blench, [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Niger-Congo/General/Niger-Congo%20an%20alternative%20view.pdf Niger-Congo: an alternative view]</ref> Connections with Bantu are mostly limited to cultural vocabulary, and several Central Sudanic words suggest that the proto-Gbaya were hunter-gatherers who acquired agriculture from the [[Sara languages|Sara]].<ref name="Moñino">Moñino (2010), [https://iaaw.hu-berlin.de/afrika/linguistik-und-sprachen/veranstaltungen/greenberg-workshop/the-position-of-gbaya-manza-ngbaka-group-among-the-niger-congo-languages The position of Gbaya-Manza-Ngbaka group among the Niger-Congo languages]</ref>

