[[File:Pratap Narayan Mishra 2013 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Pratap Narayan Mishra on a 2013 stamp of India]]
'''Pratap Narayan Mishra''' (24 September 1856 – 6 July 1894) was a [[Hindi]] essayist in British India. He is famous for exhorting all Indians to chant and believe in "Hindi, Hindu, Hindustan".<ref>{{cite book
|last1=Mayaram
|first1=Shail 
|year=2005
|title=Muslims, Dalits, and the Fabrications of History
|publisher=Orient Blackswan
|page=16
}}</ref>

His famous literary works were ''Bharat Durdasha'', ''Lokokti Shatak'', ''Shriprem Puran'', ''Prarthana Shatak'', ''Kali Kautuk'', ''Trupantam'', ''Hathi Hammir'', ''Braidala Swagat'' and ''Kanpur Mahamatya''.

