{{distinguish|Baré language|Warekena Velha language}} {{Infobox language |name=Guarequena |nativename=Warekena |states=[[Brazil]], [[Venezuela]] |speakers=650 |date=2001–2006 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Northern |fam3=[[Upper Amazon Arawakan|Upper Amazon]] |fam4=Eastern Nawiki |fam5= |iso3=gae |glotto=guar1293 |glottorefname=Guarequena }}
'''Guarequena''' (Warekena) is an [[Arawakan language]] of [[Brazil]] and [[Venezuela]]. It is one of several languages which goes by the generic name [[Baré language|Baré]].
Kaufman (1994) classified it in a Warekena group of Western Nawiki Upper Amazonian, Aikhenvald (1999) in Eastern Nawiki.
Personal pronouns in Warekena are formed by adding an emphatic suffix ''-ya'' to the cross-referencing personal prefixes.<ref>Aikenvald, Alexandra Y. 1988. "Warekena". In Desmond C. Derbyshire & Geoffrey K. Pullum (eds.), ''Handbook of Amazonian languages'', iv. 225–439. Berlin: Moutin de Gruyter. Cited in Bhat, D.N.S. 2004. ''Pronouns.'' Oxford: Oxford University Press. p. 25</ref>
